Detailed Description

The video channel is part of the display device and can be retrieved by invoking Display::GetVideoChannel. It is generally assumed that the content to be displayed via this channel is located in a separate buffer (or certain number of buffers), the process of transfering this content to the display is is called rendering and is typically assisted by hardware (e. g. a companion chip). Rendering includes some transformation like color conversion, resizing, rotation, flipping/mirroring, clipping/cropping. Most crucial for rendering is the correct mixing of the content in this channel with the display content. This is operation is called overlaying.

BOOLEAN VideoChannel::Open (  CbVideoFrameRendered  cb_frame_rendered,
void *  context
) 
 

Opens the video channel and sets the bounding rectangle for the video frames, which will be used to display the video content set by VideoChannel::RenderFrame. VideoChannel::Close should be invoked when the no frames are rendered anymore.

Parameters:
cb_frame_rendered [IN] Pointer to callback function which is called when the rendering of a frame has been completed (i. e. the frame is written to the display buffer, the transfer of frame from display buffer to LCD is not included).
context Context (e.g. this pointer) of the calling application. This context will be passed in the callback function.
Returns:
TRUE if the video channel could be opened.

CbVideoFrameRendered

BOOLEAN VideoChannel::QueryRects (  Rect &  video_frame_rect,
Rect &  crop_rect
) 
 

Reads out the capabilities of the underlying layers to fulfill a certain programming for the video rectangles. Constraints generally come in due to the utilized hardware blocks. Underlying layers try to achieve a best effort to reach the desired rectangles - if this cannot be achieved the nearest possible rectangles are returned. It is ensured, that these rectangles will never be larger. The returned rectangles can the be used in VideoChannel::SetCropRect and VideoChannel::AdjustFrameRect which guarantees that these functions will be successful.

Parameters:
video_frame_rect [IN/OUT] Position and size of screen area to be filled with video.
crop_rect [IN/OUT] Position and size of area to be cut out from the original video.
Returns:
TRUE if the setting of the parameter *would be* possible in the underlying hardware. If itwas not possible, FALSE is returned and the video frame rectangle and cropping rectangle contain the best effort of the hardware to fit the desired rectangles

void VideoChannel::RenderFrame (  void *  frame_buf,
UINT32  length,
UINT32  timestamp,
BOOLEAN  auto_release_frame = FALSE
) 
 

Renders a video frame inside the video channel. The method VideoChannel::Open must be invoked first, the method VideoChannel::Close should be invoked after the last video frame has been rendered.

Parameters:
frame_buf Pointer to the video frame buffer which will be mixed within the bounding rectangle specified by OpenVideoChannel.
length Length of the video frame buffer in bytes.
timestamp Index/timestamp of currently shown frame.
auto_release_frame if FALSE, it keeps the current frame for repeated rendering, no automatic buffer release is performed (useful for paused video)

Renders a video frame inside the video channel. The method VideoChannel::Open must be invoked first, the method VideoChannel::Close should be invoked after the last video frame has been rendered.

Parameters:
frame_buf Pointer to the video frame buffer which will be mixed within the bounding rectangle specified by OpenVideoChannel.
length Length of the video frame buffer in bytes.
timestamp Index/timestamp of currently shown frame.
auto_release_frame if FALSE, it keeps the current frame for repeated rendering, no automatic buffer release is performed (useful for paused video)

BOOLEAN VideoChannel::SetCropRect (  Rect &  crop_rect,
Rect &  effective_playback_rect
) 
 

Defines a sub rectangle within the decoded video. The coordinates are relative to the upper left corner of the video. The rectangle may never exceed the size of the decoded video i.e. the cropping rectangle must always lie completely within the video. Together with video frame rectangle this implicitly also defines a zoom factor - the content of the cropping rectangle is zoomed up or down to best fit to the video frame rectangle. This is limited by the capability of the transformation blocks for zoom and crop (i.e. in most cases the hardware).

Parameters:
crop_rect [IN/OUT] Position and size of area to be cut out from the original video.
effective_playback_rect [OUT] On return, the effective playback rect.
Returns:
TRUE if the setting of the parameter was possible in the transformation blocks. If it was not possible FALSE is returned and the cropping rectangle contains the best effort of the transformation blocks to fit to the desired rectangle.

BOOLEAN VideoChannel::SetPlaybackAndViewfinderOrder (  VideoAndViewfinderOrderType  video_viewfinder_order  ) 
 

Sets the order of the viewfinder and video playback, i.e. it specifies the order of drawing of the corresponding rectangles. It is important in case that the viewfinder and video playback rectangle are overlapping (e.g. in video telephony). If the viewfinder is not activated, this function shall be ignored.

Parameters:
video_viewfinder_order [IN] Order to be set.
Returns:
TRUE if the setting of the parameter was possible in the underlying HW. If it was not possible, FALSE is returned.
